    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "that makes sense. so basically the steel acts as a skeleton for the concrete. what happens inside the slab if the tension gets too high and the steel can't hold it? do the cracks just spread through the middle or something?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "If the tension gets too high and the steel rebar can't hold it, the cracks don't just spread randomly through the middle like a disorganized mess of spilled dirt. Instead, the failure mechanism becomes much more dramatic, and it's usually a catastrophic event, which is exactly what engineers try to prevent!\n\nWhen the tensile forces exceed the capacity of the steel—and even the steel has a breaking point, though it's much higher than the concrete's—the cracks will propagate, but they will do so in a controlled, albeit final, manner. The steel is designed to *delay* and *control* the cracking process, allowing the structure to deform under load rather than suddenly shattering. If the steel yields (stretches and deforms significantly) before it breaks, it gives you warning signs—visible deformation—before total failure.\n\nThink of it like a highly stressed band of metal holding back a massive wave of pressure. If the wave is too big, the metal will stretch until it snaps, but it won't just dissolve into dust; it will fail in a predictable way. The concrete, once cracked, will start to spall (chip away) around the rebar, and the whole system",
      "source": "target",
